<br>
 In addition to being a tribal member, I am also a citizen of the United States of America. The reason we fought for our independence from England was largely over &quot;Taxation without representation&quot;. I think that same feeling is going on now for our members living outside the 7 county service area.<br>
 If the tribe can count us for getting their federal dollars, then they can most certainly acknowledge us during election time with a fair percentage of seats on the board.<br>
 The prevailing sentiment amongst the at-large members is one of distrust of the current BOD and a lack of feeling represented on the BOD. I don't think that having to choose from a bunch of crony's in unit 1 offers me much hope for representation.<br>
 The at-large members hold a very powerful voting block if we are ever utilized correctly. I believe each prospective BOD candidate needs to state their views on this subject during the primaries. We need to know who is for fair and progressive government; or for the statu-quo, where 75% of the members have no true elected representation.<br>
 This is an idea whose time has come, if we are going to progress as a tribe.<br>
 Thanks for listening,<br>
<br>
Henry J Boulley Jr<br>
Sault Tribal Member <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCC0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsaulttribe.showUserPublicProfile?gid=egoboy@saulttribe>egoboy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#000000>(10/2/03 4:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsaulttribefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: (more about) AT-LARGE BOARD SEATS</span><hr size=1> Taxation without representation? Are you paying taxes to the Sault Tribe? Or do you mean that as a US citizen you should get back some of your federal taxes because our tribe recieves federal monies (just like all the cities, counties, states and territories do). All  tribal members  are required to be United States citizens in order to enroll. <br>
<br>
As for at-large representatives, how will I feel better represented by an individual who lives on the other side of the country, or even,( since so many of us are veterans and / or serving), outside the United States. I much prefer my elected representitive to be living within the largest concentration of my fellow tribal members, that would be unit one, where many eyes, ears and hands help them make the best decisions for the tribe as a whole. At least in unit one it is possible to authenticate who says what and are they even a tribal member.<br>
<br>
Is our tribe wealthy today? Yes, relative to how my father's generation fared. No, compared to some other tribes. Are we many in numbers? Yes, compared to some tribes here on the west coast that have fewer than 10 members. No, if you consider, &quot;Detroit's metropolitan area had a population of 5,456,400 in 2000. The metropolitan area also includes significant minority groups, including the largest community of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Arab Americans</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> in the nation, numbering 102,000<br>
people in 2000.&quot; (source is &quot;Detroit (city, Michigan),&quot; Microsoft® Encarta® Online Encyclopedia 2003<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://encarta.msn.com">encarta.msn.com</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> © 1997-2003 Microsoft Corporation. All Rights Reserved.) Put another way, there are 3.4 Arab Americans living in Detroit alone, compared to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>all</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of our tribal members in the world (rounding our membership to 30,000).<br>
<br>
Now, more than ever, the admonition to, &quot;give only your very best advice, in counsel,&quot; applies. I live in Washington state, home to many tribes left relatively intact by history. The in-fighting and back biting in some tribes almost assures they will not survive. I mean to do all I can to insure my tribes survival as a flourishing and vibrant people. <br>
<br>
Robert L Stearns Jr ap Oshawawano<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFF0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsaulttribe.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ixolabrat>IxoLabRat</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#000000>(10/9/03 3:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsaulttribefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: (more about) AT-LARGE BOARD SEATS</span><hr size=1> While I admit, that the statement &quot;Taxation without Representation&quot; is factually incorrect because we do not pay taxes to the Tribe. I was using it as the basis of what it was really intended for: The basic right of &quot;Actual Representation&quot; versus &quot;Virtual Representation&quot;.<br>
<br>
I realize that it would be ineffective government to have at-large BOD and expect them to govern/contribute from their current location. The at-large BOD would have to relocate temporarily to be able to conduct government business. That is one of basic foundations of citizen government. In today's mass transit society; I don't see the difference between living in Marquette and being on the BOD, or living in Iowa and being on the board...as long as I can be where I have to be, when I have to be.<br>
<br>
I don't put much faith in the analogy of: &quot;I much prefer my elected representitive to be living within the largest concentration of my fellow tribal members, that would be unit one, where many eyes, ears and hands help them make the best decisions for the tribe as a whole. At least in unit one it is possible to authenticate who says what and are they even a tribal member.&quot;<br>
<br>
So far the eyes and ears of unit one have been dubious at best, and thatis why we are in the shape we are in. It is in not having enough checks and balances in place. It is your right to be able to vote for someone in unit one. I have no problem with that. It is just that I also believe that I have the right to vote for whatever tribal member I think will do the best job (irregardless of where he lives).<br>
<br>
I also think it would be virtually impossible for a non-member to run, since you'll have to go to the Soo to register and fill out all sorts of forms (I would imagine). You'll have to show your tribal membership card at some point in the process, and that should really be the bottom line. <br>
<br>
These are tough times that our tribe and it's elected goverment are facing. Who knows all or some of the answers to our problems. That is a very good question. I for one think it's very bad business to eliminate the vast majority of our members from being able to assist our tribe, by not even being able to run for a seat on the BOD.<br>
<br>
HJB <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCC0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsaulttribe.showUserPublicProfile?gid=chippewa1>chippewa 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#000000>(12/18/03 8:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsaulttribefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   At Large Representation</span><hr size=1> Mr. Boulley,<br>
Thanks for your reply. I thought I was the only one that felt the outside members were being ignored. Certainly traveling to the UP once or twice a month isn't a huge problem for me, coming from Lansing or any other city. Anyone aware of the 1836 treaty boundaries can see that almost 2/3's of the lower peninsula is within these boundaries. Why are the treaty boundaries not the service area?. A strong point should have been made when negotiations took place with the federal government many years ago. These boundaries should have never been deviated from in any negotiations since they are historic. The tax agreement should of had the same boundaries. I believe these boundaries would ultimately be upheld in Federal court since the 1836 treaty and all of its specifics have stood the test of time each time the courts have taken up legal opinions. Please respond with any opinions.<br>
<br>
1SGT Charles Janeski<br>
